result.execSummary:
The defendant Jordan J Alix was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Chippewa County Case No. 15CM292 is dismissed and read-in.

miscConds.notes: Defendant to set up a payment plan within thirty (30) days with Probation Agent.  Plus supervision fees.    If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due. All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.  $200 represents the mandatory DNA Surcharge.
Any assessment and counseling as required and follow through and complete all required treatment.

Not to possess or consume any alcohol.  Not to go on any premises where primary purpose is the sale of alcohol.  Not to possess or consume any illegal drugs or any prescription drugs not prescribed.  Not to possess any drug paraphernalia.
